THE MODERATOR: All right, everyone, we're here with Jin Young Ko, the Rolex No. 1 player. Jin Young, this has been an incredible, incredible year for you. Four wins, already clinched player of the year; 12 Top 10s, so you won the leaders Top 10 Award.   
79% greens in regulation; just over a 69% scoring average. Is it possible for you to pick a single highlight, one highlight of your year?   
JIN YOUNG KO: I would say four wins and then two majors, yeah.   
THE MODERATOR: Yeah. What about those experiences, those four wins, really stands out to you? Started at Founder's Cup then a win at ANA, a win at Evian, a win in Canada. What about those was so special for you?   
JIN YOUNG KO: Bank of Hope was first time win to the States, then second one ANA, first major; Evian, second major; last one, bogey-free round. Also 114 holes bogey-free. That is really special to me.   
THE MODERATOR: That is so hard to comprehended, to understand, 114 holes bogey-free. When you think back on it, are you surprised you were able to do that? That was amazing.   
JIN YOUNG KO: Yeah, it was incredible. I think was in August and I didn't think too much about bogey. Like think about shots other than bogey, par or birdie. That's all I could do. I didn't think about bogey at all.   
THE MODERATOR: So the answer being I didn't think about birdie. I thought about any shot other than a bogey. So that's what got you through.   
But earlier this year in Australia you said your goal was to be the happiest player on the golf course. Did you meet that goal?   
JIN YOUNG KO: Yeah, I think so.   
THE MODERATOR: What about you makes you such a happy player?   
JIN YOUNG KO: Just life. That is really -- I'm happy because I'm alive. I want to thank everything about being alive.   
THE MODERATOR: You're happy because you're alive, because of your fans and your friends. I know you believe in God. Those are all things that drive you in your life to be happy?   
JIN YOUNG KO: For sure. Of course, uh-huh.   
THE MODERATOR: We come here to Tiburon where you've played well, but you're coming in off three weeks off. Very tired I'm sure at the end of a long season.   
How do you feel as you come here this week and the season-ending event?   
JIN YOUNG KO: Last year I finish this tournament and I stay two weeks more with short game coach and with my parents and her. So my feeling is just over 2018 and this week, like I can't believe between last year and this tournament, like between other tournament.   
So like...   
INTERPRETER: (Indiscernible.)   
THE MODERATOR: Okay, so just thinking combined to last year as well.   
JIN YOUNG KO: Yeah. So my feeling is first tournament of the year.   
THE MODERATOR: Oh, okay. Really? That's interesting. Are you feeling well physically with your time off?   
JIN YOUNG KO: I was withdraw in Taiwan. My ankle was weaker and still weaker, too, so I did ice every night 20 minutes with the ice.   
So I hopefully getting better, and then but this week is last, so will be fine.   
THE MODERATOR: Open it up for questions.   
 Q.  How did you injure your ankle and how much pain do you feel just walking around in daily life?  
JIN YOUNG KO: Like here and then outside, so when I hit the ball and I did finish, and then like too tight here, so painful like outside. Then sometimes walk and then painful inside.   
So don't know. I need to rest.   
 Q.  Were you worried at any point that you might not be able to play this week?  
JIN YOUNG KO: Yeah. Yeah, uh-huh, and still worried a little bit.   
 Q.  Oh, wow. How did you do it? How did you hurt your ankle?  
JIN YOUNG KO: I don't know. Just I practice swing at the Taiwan No. 18 from the tee and then I couldn't swing again. Then I said to (indiscernible), Can you hit ahead from me? Then she said, Yeah, and then I rest maybe one minute or 50 second, and then I hit the ball from the tee and then I walked; a little bit still painful.   
So after round I went to the physical and locker and I had massage and then I did tape my leg to legs. Then I sleep -- I slept but still pain, but I shoot 1-over so I want to try get under par second round or third round.   
But after second round like more painful, and then third round I had tape in the morning and then I hit maybe 11 holes, I played 11 holes and then I can't. I couldn't anymore.   
So I said to caddie, I can't play anymore. He said, Okay, you don't have to play. You need rest. Because in Taiwan was my fifth week, so he knew. Then I play three weeks in Korea and then back two weeks playing Korea and back to China and back to BMW and then Taiwan.   
So he knows. And then after withdraw and then I go back to Korea, straight go to Korea, and then on Sunday rest and on Monday I go -- I went to hospital and then I was shot in my ankles. Yeah, just rest all week.   
Then I practice maybe just one or two days on Monday and Tuesday and then I was here.   
THE MODERATOR: We're glad to have you back then.   
 Q.  It's hard to be happy when you're getting shot in your ankle, right?  
JIN YOUNG KO: Yeah.   
